body:
1. Create new Flutter app in IJ
1. Hit Run
1. Open the Flutter view
1. Click the 'Open Observatory timeline' button

=> a 'blank' browser window is opened

comment_data.body: @mit-mit, I'm not able to repro this, either run or debug, w/ iOS simulator, android devices, or the android emulator.
Can someone else try also? I got a consistent repro.
Does the address look well formed? Does the observatory web ui respond in general? And, can you get the the observatory timeline page when you flutter run from the command-line?
It's not timeline specific, the general observatory button in the Console doesn't work either. The address is empty, so no. Also, I don't see the observatory URL printed in the Console.
If I `flutter run` from the terminal, the URL is printed and it opens just fine.

> The address is empty

Ok, that sounds like a IntelliJ platform bug. 

https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/blob/4118d2df4b768c3ddf7ebd9b1b82db7d08d4a998/src/io/flutter/run/OpenObservatoryAction.java#L53

We're trying to open the url with any chrome browser (that IntelliJ knows about), and then fallback to any browser.
@mit-mit, I don't think this is a regression in the plugin per se, so moving out of M17. We can patch the release if we do find an issue in the flutter plugin.

This is still a 100% repro for me. Can you try in macOS against an iOS Simulator? I do not get an Observatory URL in the console output when running from IJ, and the Observatory button still launches an empty browser tab.

I'll re-try, but I originally did try macos and ios simulator. What version of IntelliJ are you using? Do you see any obvious issues in your 'Web Browsers' pref page in IntelliJ?

> I do not get an Observatory URL in the console output when running from IJ

You won't - we filter this for less noise (user's can open Observatory other ways).

I'm using IDEA Community 2017.2.1.

I don't see any issues in the browser preference.
I'm seeing new behavior (from ~2 weeks ago): https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/12048 - I'm not able to get to any observatory pages.
@devoncarew this appears to still be broken in the M18 RC build

I just tried this on my Mac using IntelliJ with the M18 RC plugin. Everything seems to work.

I tried both the 'Open Observatory' and 'Observatory Timeline' buttons. The expected pages opened in Chrome.

I set a breakpoint in IntelliJ, ran to it, saw that the Observatory recognized the breakpoint, opened the Observatory debugger, continued. Then something happened that I didn't expect: the IntelliJ debugger did not recognize the program was running, it still showed the stack. The timeline seemed to work. Other than the IJ debugger not getting updated everything was fine.

I did 'flutter upgrade' yesterday so both my Flutter and Dart SDK are current.

> this appears to still be broken in the M18 RC build

Michael, I've never been able to repro this :( We haven't had reports from users, so I don't think this is a widespread issue.

Do other things that open a browser work? Flutter > Tools > send feedback?
I did a bit more testing. It works as expected for me on my Windows and home Mac. But still tails on the office Mac.

Back on the office Mac, it's still failing. *Help > Flutter Plugin Help* and *Tools > Flutter > Submit Feedback* work fine though.

One potential cause: On this machine where it's failing I'm using Chrome Beta (62.0.3202.45).

> Back on the office Mac, it's still failing. Help > Flutter Plugin Help and Tools > Flutter > Submit Feedback work fine though.

That's good data though - at least that mechanism for launching web pages works. For the observatory, I think we're preferring a chrome browser if we can find one.
blank on Linux/Chrome/Android.  I'm using VSCode Open Observatory timeline.

rename.from: Open Observatory timeline is broken in Run mode

title: Opening Observatory is broken
